The best approach for `File.*` and `Directory.*` is the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and already covers all three calls.

## Setup

**1. Install packages:**
```
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <TestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

**2. Register in DI** (Program.cs / Startup.cs):
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

**3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes:**
```csharp
public class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Read(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Write(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool DirectoryExists(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

**4. Test with `MockFileSystem`:**
```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});
// Pre-create directories as needed
mockFs.Directory.CreateDirectory("/output");

var service = new MyService(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", service.Read("/data/config.json"));
Assert.True(service.DirectoryExists("/output"));

service.Write("/output/result.txt", "done");
Assert.Equal("done", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/output/result.txt"));
```

## Why this over a custom wrapper?

| Custom `IFileWrapper` | `System.IO.Abstractions` |
|---|---|
| You maintain it | Community-maintained, well-tested |
| Covers only what you wrap today | Full `System.IO` surface already wrapped |
| Need to extend as you use new APIs | Already complete |

The key rule: **only inject `IFileSystem`** — one interface covers `File`, `Directory`, `Path`, and more. No need for separate abstractions per static class.
